======================================================================
TEST 4: GROWTH OPERATOR — VERTEX ADDITION
======================================================================

When we add a vertex v to an n-tournament to get an (n+1)-tournament,
we must choose n new arc directions (v→i or i→v for each existing vertex i).
This gives 2^n choices. Most lead to the same iso class.

KEY QUESTION: How many DISTINCT iso classes at n+1 can be reached
by extending a given iso class at n?

From our data (number of distinct n+1 classes reachable from each n class):


n=3 → n=4 extension:
  Class 0 → 4 distinct classes at n=4
  Class 1 → 3 distinct classes at n=4
  Total distinct n=4 classes reachable: 4

n=4 → n=5 extension:
  Class 0 → 9 distinct classes at n=5
  Class 1 → 6 distinct classes at n=5
  Class 2 → 8 distinct classes at n=5
  Class 3 → 6 distinct classes at n=5
  Total distinct n=5 classes reachable: 12

n=5 → n=6 extension:
  Class 0 → 21 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 1 → 13 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 2 → 23 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 3 → 13 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 4 → 24 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 5 → 23 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 6 → 21 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 7 → 13 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 8 → 23 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 9 → 13 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 10 → 21 distinct classes at n=6
  Class 11 → 7 distinct classes at n=6
  Total distinct n=6 classes reachable: 56

